        <tr><td>E02</td><td>NTC temperature sensor</td><td>Sensor replacement, $200 to $340</td></tr>
        <tr><td>E04</td><td>Flow meter fault</td><td>Inlet valve or flow meter, $200 to $380</td></tr>
        <tr><td>E05</td><td>Overfill detected</td><td>Float switch or inlet valve stuck open, $260 to $420</td></tr>
        <tr><td>E06</td><td>Door switch fault</td><td>Door latch assembly, $260 to $440</td></tr>
        <tr><td>E09</td><td>Heater circuit fault</td><td>Heating element or board, $260 to $820</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>E15</strong></td><td><strong>Leak detected (flood sensor in base pan)</strong></td><td><strong>Most common Bosch service code. Water in base pan from any leak source. Diagnostic identifies which.</strong></td></tr>
        <tr><td>E16</td><td>Inlet valve stuck open / overfill</td><td>Inlet valve replacement, $200 to $340</td></tr>
        <tr><td>E22</td><td>Filter blocked, residual water in sump</td><td>Filter cleaning, $89 diagnostic only typically</td></tr>
        <tr><td>E23</td><td>Drain pump fault</td><td>Drain pump, $260 to $440</td></tr>
        <tr><td>E24</td><td>Drain hose blocked or kinked</td><td>Hose service, $180 to $280</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p class="note"><strong>E15 specifically:</strong> Bosch's most common service call. The flood sensor in the base pan triggers and locks the unit. Resetting requires water removal from the pan plus underlying leak repair. We see E15 about 12 to 18 times per month across the LA service area.</p>
  </div>
</section>

